'''South Middlesex Opportunities Council''', commonly referred to as '''SMOC''',is one of the largest private, non-profit [[social services]] groups in Eastern Massachusetts. Operating in the Metrowest region of the state, the group provides homeless shelters, drug rehabilitation programs, family counseling handicapped transportation and numerous other social services.

==Programs==
* '''Joan Brack Adult Learning Center''' GED classes for adults who do not have a high school diploma. Receives financial support from the Brack Family Foundation and [[Middlesex Savings Bank]].<ref name="mwdn-jbalc">{{cite news |url=http://www.metrowestdailynews.com/photos/x621501875/Joan-Brack-Adult-Learning-Center-graduation |title=Joan Brack Adult Learning Center graduation |first=Alan |last=Jung |date=23 June 2010 |work=Metrowest Daily News |accessdate=18 October 2010}}</ref>
* '''Larry's Place'''' A respite for homeless [[veterans]] in in [[Framingham]]. Provides services to help military veterans with substance abuse, mental health counseling and job skills.<ref name="mwdn-larry's">{{cite news |url=http://www.metrowestdailynews.com/news/x1659498417/Larrys-Place-A-respite-for-homeless-veterans |title=Larrys Place - A respite for homeless veterans |first=Dan |last=McDonald |date=12 November 2009 |work=Metrowest Daily News |accessdate=18 October 2010}}</ref>
* '''New Beginnings''' A permanent congregate housing program for homeless living with HIV or AIDS.<ref name="mwdn-new beginnings">{{cite news |url=http://www.metrowestdailynews.com/news/x1810246237/Life-Learning-Framingham-school-pairs-housing-education-programs |title=Life Learning- Framingham school pairs housing education programs |first=Dan |last=McDonald |date=09 June 2009 |work=Metrowest Daily News |accessdate=18 October 2010}}</ref> located at the [[Bethany Hill School]] in [[Framingham]]
* '''Pathways Family Shelter''' is a fourteen family congregate shelter for homeless families.
* '''Sage House''' is a shelter providing substance abuse treatment and supportive services for seven homeless families
* '''Serenity House''' Residential long-term treatment program for 20-30 women with HIV/AIDS and for pregnant/postpartum women located in [[Hopkinton]]. Includes residential beds for clients' children.<ref>http://alcoholism.about.com/od/tx_ma/qt/ma044.htm</ref>
* '''Turning Point program''' A 18-bed emergency shelter for single adult men.<ref name="mwdn-larry's"/>
* '''Voices Against Violence''' A program in Framingham for domestic violence victims.
* '''The Wright Home for Women''' A 16-bed shelter for single adult women. Residents are required to engage in an intensive, comprehensive program designed to assist participants over a nine to twelve month period work to achieve the goal of economic self-sufficiency. The property is a drug and alcohol-free environment located in [[Easthampton]]

